**What was patched**

`core/src/main/java/org/apache/druid/js/JavaScriptConfig.java` — single file change.

**Root cause**: Jackson's `@JacksonInject` mechanism can be overridden by an empty key `""` in user-supplied JSON. When a request body contains `"": {"enabled": true}`, Jackson uses that to replace the Guice-injected `JavaScriptConfig` with a user-controlled one where `enabled=true`, bypassing `druid.javascript.enabled=false`.

**Fix**: Added a static `volatile boolean javascriptDisabledByServer` flag. When Guice initializes `JavaScriptConfig` with `enabled=false` (the default), this flag is set permanently. `isEnabled()` checks this flag first — so even if an attacker injects a `JavaScriptConfig(enabled=true)` via the `""` key exploit, `isEnabled()` still returns `false`.

The logic is safe against the static initializer ordering issue: `ENABLED_INSTANCE = new JavaScriptConfig(true)` runs at class load time but doesn't set the flag (since `enabled=true` → `!enabled` is false). The flag only gets set when Guice creates the config with `enabled=false`."}}
